Schedule Volatility, Front-loading, and Household Wellbeing

data_path <- "C:/Users/jingy/Dropbox/VIP/09. Main study/09. Data/20. Generated/simon_analysis/30_merged_panel-hh_id-period.dta"
if (!file.exists(data_path)) stop("Error: Data file not found at: ", data_path)
data <- read_dta(data_path)
cat("Loaded:", nrow(data), "rows x", ncol(data), "columns\n")
data_analysis <- data %>%
    mutate(
        group_label = case_when(
            control == 1 ~ "Control",
            predictable == 1 & period == 0 ~ "Baseline",
            predictable == 1 & high_draw == 1 ~ "High Draw",
            predictable == 1 & high_draw == 0 ~ "Low Draw",
            TRUE ~ "Unknown"
        ),
        period_label = case_when(
            period == 0 ~ "Period 0 (Baseline)",
            TRUE ~ paste0("Period ", period)
        )
    )
schedule_chars <- data %>%
    filter(predictable == 1, period > 0) %>%
    arrange(hh_id, period) %>%
    group_by(schedule) %>%
    summarise(
        prop_high = mean(high_draw, na.rm = TRUE),
        n_switches = mean(
            tapply(high_draw, hh_id, function(x) sum(abs(diff(x)), na.rm = TRUE)),
            na.rm = TRUE
        ),
        front_loading = mean(
            tapply(seq_along(high_draw), hh_id, function(idx) {
                hd <- high_draw[idx]
                w <- rev(seq_along(hd))
                weighted.mean(hd, w = w, na.rm = TRUE)
            }),
            na.rm = TRUE
        ),
        .groups = "drop"
    ) %>%
    mutate(
        volatility_cat = case_when(
            n_switches <= 1 ~ "Low Volatility (<=1 switch)",
            n_switches <= 3 ~ "Medium Volatility (2-3 switches)",
            TRUE ~ "High Volatility (>=4 switches)"
        ),
        timing_cat = case_when(
            front_loading > 0.55 ~ "Front-loaded (High draws early)",
            front_loading < 0.45 ~ "Back-loaded (High draws late)",
            TRUE ~ "Balanced timing"
        ),
        vol_fl = n_switches * front_loading,
        vol_fl_grp = cut(vol_fl,
            breaks = quantile(vol_fl, probs = c(0, 1 / 3, 2 / 3, 1), na.rm = TRUE),
            labels = c("Low composite", "Medium composite", "High composite"),
            include.lowest = TRUE
        )
    )

data_analysis <- data_analysis %>%
    left_join(
        schedule_chars %>%
            select(schedule, volatility_cat, timing_cat,
                   n_switches, front_loading, vol_fl, vol_fl_grp),
        by = "schedule"
    )

1 Introduction

This document investigates whether the shape of an assigned income schedule not just total income causally affects mental health and household wellbeing in the VIP predictable-schedule study.

Each household in the predictable arm is randomly assigned to one of 20 income schedules. Every schedule spans 6 periods and contains exactly 3 High (H) and 3 Low (L) draw periods, so total income is equalized across all households by design. What varies is the ordering of draws. Because assignment is random, any systematic differences in outcomes across schedules must be caused by the schedule shape itself.

The document is organised as follows: Section 2 defines the three schedule-shape measures, presents the main decomposition regression, and shows how each components effect evolves across the 6 periods. Section 3 presents the ICC analysis a complementary way to quantify how much outcome variance schedules explain.

2 Key Measures and Main Result

2.1 Definitions

We characterise each schedule using three constructed variables. These are computed once per schedule (averaging over all households assigned to it) and then merged into the household-period panel.

n_switches Income Volatility

The number of HL transitions in the 6-period draw sequence. This ranges from 1 (HHHLLL: one HL switch at the midpoint) to 5 (HLHLHL: income alternates every single period). A higher value means a more volatile income path households face frequent reversals between high and low income states. This is the measure most intuitively associated with instability.

Why it matters for mental health: Frequent reversals may cause repeated cycles of raised and dashed expectations. Even if households know their schedule in advance, adapting behaviour to a highly volatile sequence is cognitively and practically demanding.

front_loading Income Timing

A position-weighted mean of the draw sequence, assigning higher weight to earlier periods:

\[\text{front_loading} = \frac{\sum_{t=1}^{6}(7-t)\cdot \mathbf{1}[\text{draw}_t = H]}{\sum_{t=1}^{6}(7-t)} = \frac{6 \cdot d_1 + 5 \cdot d_2 + 4 \cdot d_3 + 3 \cdot d_4 + 2 \cdot d_5 + 1 \cdot d_6}{21}\]

where \(d_t = 1\) if period \(t\) is a High draw and 0 otherwise. Reference values:

Schedule Pattern front_loading
HHHLLL H early 0.71
HLHLHL Alternating 0.57
LLLHHH H late 0.29

A value close to 1 means H draws are concentrated early (front-loaded); close to 0 means H draws come late (back-loaded); 0.5 means balanced timing.

Why it matters: A front-loaded household receives abundant income early but then endures a prolonged stretch of low income potentially feeling like a deprivation relative to earlier periods. The opposite holds for back-loaded households, who might experience low income early as normal, then enjoy a later windfall.

vol_fl Composite Index

\[\text{vol_fl} = n\_switches \times front\_loading\]

This composite is large only when a schedule is both frequently alternating and front-loaded. The intuition: volatile switching is most psychologically disruptive when it begins from a position of early high income the household experiences repeated downward reversals from an established high baseline. A highly volatile but back-loaded schedule partially cancels out, since income starts low and the volatility is less salient. For regression, vol_fl is standardised to mean 0, SD 1.

Summary: vol_fl captures the worst-case schedule shape many switches AND high draws concentrated early. It is our primary summary index, and the decomposition below separates the contribution of each component.

2.2 Decomposition: Volatility vs Front-loading vs Current Draw

The composite vol_fl bundles two distinct schedule features. The table below separates their contributions using five specifications per outcome. This is the main result of the document.

Column Regressors Question answered
(1) vol_fl composite only Does the combined index predict outcomes?
(2) switches n_switches only Is volatility (frequency of switching) sufficient?
(3) front_load front_loading only Is timing (H draws early vs late) sufficient?
(4) decomp both components Which dominates when both are included simultaneously?
(5) full both + high_draw Does schedule shape survive controlling for whether the household is currently in a High draw period?

Column (5) is a robustness check: high_draw = 1 in periods when the household is currently receiving the High income draw. If the effect of vol_fl were purely mechanical simply reflecting that High draw periods have higher income it should disappear once we control for high_draw. Persistence in column (5) indicates genuine structural effects of schedule shape beyond the current-period draw.

data_reg2 <- data_reg %>%

        fl_std = as.numeric(scale(front_loading))

fit_decomp <- function(y, spec) {
    fml <- switch(spec,
        vfl    = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ vol_fl_std               | period")),
        sw     = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ sw_std                   | period")),
        fl     = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ fl_std                   | period")),
        decomp = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ sw_std + fl_std          | period")),
        full   = as.formula(paste0(y, " ~ sw_std + fl_std + high_draw | period"))
    )
    tryCatch(feols(fml, cluster = ~hh_id, data = data_reg2), error = function(e) NULL)
}

specs  <- c("vfl", "sw", "fl", "decomp", "full")
sp_sfx <- c("(1) vol_fl", "(2) switches", "(3) front_load", "(4) decomp", "(5) full")

build_decomp <- function(outcomes_named) {
    mods <- list()
    for (y in names(outcomes_named)) {
        nm <- outcomes_named[[y]]
        for (i in seq_along(specs)) {
            mods[[paste0(nm, " | ", sp_sfx[i])]] <- fit_decomp(y, specs[i])
        }
    }
    Filter(Negate(is.null), mods)
}

2.3 Dynamic Effects: How Each Components Impact Evolves by Period

The regression tables above pool all 6 periods together. This section asks: does the effect of each predictor grow, fade, or reverse over time? For each period (16), we run a cross-sectional OLS regression with one predictor at a time the composite (vol_fl), volatility (n_switches), or front-loading and plot the resulting coefficients with 95% CIs. Comparing the three lines reveals which component drives effects early vs late in the study.

plot_predictors <- c("vol_fl_std", "sw_std", "fl_std")
pred_labels     <- c(
    vol_fl_std = "vol_fl (composite)",
    sw_std     = "N switches (volatility)",
    fl_std     = "Front-loading"
)
pred_colors <- c(
    "vol_fl (composite)"      = "#7B1FA2",
    "N switches (volatility)" = "#C62828",
    "Front-loading"           = "#1976D2"
)

# For each outcome  period  predictor, fit a separate cross-sectional regression
dyn_decomp <- lapply(names(decomp_outcomes), function(outcome) {
    lapply(1:6, function(p) {
        sub <- data_reg2 %>% filter(period == p)
        if (!outcome %in% names(sub) || nrow(sub) < 10) return(NULL)
        lapply(plot_predictors, function(pred) {
            fml <- as.formula(paste0(outcome, " ~ ", pred))
            m   <- tryCatch(feols(fml, cluster = ~hh_id, data = sub),
                            error = function(e) NULL)
            if (is.null(m)) return(NULL)
            b  <- coef(m)[pred]
            se <- sqrt(vcov(m)[pred, pred])
            data.frame(outcome = outcome, period = p, predictor = pred,
                       coef = b, se = se, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
        }) %>% dplyr::bind_rows()
    }) %>% dplyr::bind_rows()
}) %>%
    dplyr::bind_rows() %>%
    mutate(
        OutcomeLabel = factor(decomp_outcomes[outcome], levels = decomp_outcomes),
        PredLabel    = factor(pred_labels[predictor],
                              levels = pred_labels[plot_predictors]),
        lo95 = coef - 1.96 * se,
        hi95 = coef + 1.96 * se
    )

plot_decomp_dyn <- function(outcome_keys, title_str, ncols = 2, h = 4) {
    df <- dyn_decomp %>%
        filter(outcome %in% outcome_keys) %>%
        mutate(OutcomeLabel = droplevels(OutcomeLabel))
    ggplot(df, aes(x = period, y = coef,
                   color = PredLabel, fill = PredLabel)) +
        geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed",
                   color = "gray60", linewidth = 0.4) +
        geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = lo95, ymax = hi95),
                    alpha = 0.10, color = NA) +
        geom_line(linewidth = 0.9) +
        geom_point(size = 2.5) +
        scale_x_continuous(breaks = 1:6, labels = paste0("P", 1:6)) +
        scale_color_manual(values = pred_colors, name = NULL) +
        scale_fill_manual(values  = pred_colors, name = NULL) +
        facet_wrap(~OutcomeLabel, scales = "fixed", ncol = ncols) +
        labs(
            title    = title_str,
            subtitle = paste0(
                "Each line = one predictor run separately per period | ",
                "95% CI shaded | SEs clustered at HH\n",
                "Purple = composite vol_fl  |  Red = N switches  |  Blue = front-loading"
            ),
            x = "Period", y = "Coefficient (std.)"
        ) +
        theme_minimal(base_size = 11) +
        theme(
            strip.text       = element_text(face = "bold", size = 10),
            panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
            legend.position  = "bottom",
            plot.title       = element_text(face = "bold"),
            plot.subtitle    = element_text(size = 8.5, color = "gray40")
        )
}

plot_decomp_dyn(c("phq2_z", "gad2_z"),

)

3 ICC Analysis: How Much Variance Do Schedules Explain?

3.1 What the ICC Measures

The Intra-Class Correlation (ICC) answers: of all the variation in an outcome across households and time periods, what fraction is explained by which schedule group the household was assigned to?

We fit a null mixed model for each outcome and grouping dimension a model with only a random intercept for the group, no other predictors:

\[\text{outcome}_{it} = \mu + \alpha_{g(i)} + \varepsilon_{it}\]

where \(\alpha_{g(i)} \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\text{between}})\) is a random effect for schedule group \(g\) and \(\varepsilon_{it} \sim N(0, \sigma^2_{\text{within}})\) is the residual. The ICC is then:

\[\text{ICC} = \frac{\sigma^2_{\text{between}}}{\sigma^2_{\text{between}} + \sigma^2_{\text{within}}}\]

Plain English: ICC is the share of total variance attributable to group membership.

  • ICC = 2% 2% of total variation in the outcome is explained by schedule assignment; the remaining 98% is within-schedule variation (household-to-household differences unrelated to which schedule they received).
  • ICC = 50% equal split between between-schedule and within-schedule variance.
  • ICC = 99% nearly all variation is between schedule groups; households on the same schedule behave almost identically.

Question: Does 1% mean the ratio of variance within a schedule is 1% of across schedules? No. The ICC is the ratio of between-group variance to total variance, not within to between. A 1% ICC means \(\sigma^2_{\text{between}}\) is 1% of total, and \(\sigma^2_{\text{within}}\) is 99% of total i.e., within-schedule variance is about 99 times larger than between-schedule variance, meaning schedules explain very little. (If within were 1% of across, that would correspond to an ICC near 99%, not 1%.)

3.2 How It Is Computed

The ICC is extracted using icc() from the performance package (part of the easystats suite), which is the standard R function for this purpose. It fits the null mixed model via lmer() from lme4 and returns ICC_adjusted = _between / (_between + _within). There is no need for a custom function this is a well-tested, standard computation.

3.3 How to Read the Table

Rows are outcomes grouped by domain. Columns are four different ways of grouping the 20 schedules:

Column Groups What it tests
Raw Schedule (20 groups) 20 distinct schedules Maximum specificity treats each schedule as unique
Volatility (# switches) 3 bins: Low / Medium / High Does how often income switches capture schedule differences?
Timing (Front vs Back) 3 bins: Front / Balanced / Back Does when H draws occur capture schedule differences?
Volatility Front-loading 3 bins of vol_fl Does the composite index capture schedule differences?

What to look for: If the Volatility Front-loading column has a similar ICC to Raw Schedule (20 groups), the composite index captures almost as much schedule-level variance as knowing the exact schedule confirming it is a good summary of what actually differs across schedules. Comparing columns also reveals which dimension (volatility vs timing) is the stronger driver of between-schedule differences.

A note on NA cells: An NA cell means the ICC could not be estimated for that outcomegrouping combination. This happens when the mixed model (lmer) fails to fit most commonly because the outcome variable has too many missing values in that subgroup, the grouping variable collapses to effectively one level, or there is near-zero residual variation. NA is not a substantive result; it simply means there was insufficient information to calculate the ICC for that cell.

# Uses performance::icc()  the standard package function.
# For a null mixed model lmer(y ~ 1 + (1|group)), icc()$ICC_adjusted equals
# var_between / (var_between + var_within), which is the standard ICC1.
#
# NAs arise from "singular" lmer fits: when between-group variance is estimated
# as exactly 0, performance::icc() returns NA rather than 0. A singular fit
# simply means no detectable between-group variance, i.e. ICC = 0%, so we
# replace those NAs with 0. Singularity warnings are suppressed accordingly.
calc_icc <- function(outcome, group_var, data) {
    if (!outcome %in% names(data) || !group_var %in% names(data)) return(NA_real_)
    sub <- data[!is.na(data[[outcome]]) & !is.na(data[[group_var]]), ]
    if (nrow(sub) < 10 || sd(sub[[outcome]], na.rm = TRUE) == 0) return(NA_real_)
    tryCatch({
        m <- suppressWarnings(
            lmer(as.formula(paste0(outcome, " ~ 1 + (1 | ", group_var, ")")),
                 data = sub, REML = TRUE)
        )
        icc_val <- suppressMessages(performance::icc(m)$ICC_adjusted)
        # Singular fit  var_between = 0  ICC = 0, not NA
        if (is.na(icc_val)) 0 else icc_val
    }, error = function(e) NA_real_)
}

grouping_vars   <- c("schedule", "volatility_cat", "timing_cat", "vol_fl_grp")
grouping_labels <- c(
    schedule       = "Raw Schedule\n(20 groups)",
    volatility_cat = "Volatility\n(# switches)",
    timing_cat     = "Timing\n(Front vs Back)",

icc_table <- expand.grid(
    Outcome  = icc_outcomes,
    Grouping = grouping_vars,
    stringsAsFactors = FALSE
) %>%
    rowwise() %>%
    mutate(ICC = calc_icc(Outcome, Grouping, icc_data)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    mutate(
        OutcomeLabel  = outcome_labels[Outcome],
        GroupingLabel = grouping_labels[Grouping],
        Category      = case_when(
            Outcome %in% c("phq2_z", "gad2_z")                         ~ "Mental Health",
            Outcome %in% c("days_worked", "working_adults_corrected")   ~ "Labor",
            TRUE                                                         ~ "Financial"
        )
    ) %>%
    arrange(Category, Outcome, Grouping) %>%
    select(Category, OutcomeLabel, GroupingLabel, ICC)

icc_wide <- icc_table %>%
    tidyr::pivot_wider(names_from = GroupingLabel, values_from = ICC)

icc_wide %>%
    gt() %>%
    tab_header(
        title    = "ICC by Outcome and Schedule Grouping Dimension",
        subtitle = "Each cell = share of total variance in the outcome explained by schedule group assignment"
    ) %>%
    fmt_percent(columns = where(is.numeric), decimals = 1) %>%
    cols_label(Category = "Domain", OutcomeLabel = "Outcome") %>%
    tab_style(style = cell_text(weight = "bold"), locations = cells_column_labels()) %>%
    tab_spanner(label = "Grouping Dimension (ICC = % of total variance between groups)",
                columns = 3:6) %>%
    tab_options(table.width = pct(100)) %>%
    print()
